com.camerontec.util.collection

Class ByteArrayStoreToCachingMapAdapter<K,V>

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.camerontec.util.collection.ByteArrayStoreToCachingMapAdapter<K,V>
  • Type Parameters:
    K - Type of the Key element.
    V - Type of the Value element.
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    ICompactable, Closeable, AutoCloseable, Map<K,V>

    public class ByteArrayStoreToCachingMapAdapter<K,V>
extends Object
implements Map<K,V>, Closeable, ICompactable
    A Map implementation which adapts to a underlying IByteArrayStore implementation.

    If a cache is supplied during construction then this implementation delegates read requests to the cache, only resorting to the backing store on a cache miss. Likewise, entries are added to the cache on insertion and also refreshed on key access.

    All accesses to the cache (if any) are thread safe.

    This implementation does not support the following operations:

    • values()

    An UnsupportedOperationException is thrown if either is called.

    This implementation assumes that custom IBytesSegmentExternalizers and the backing store are all thread safe.

    The implementation of keySet() provided is particularly costly since it involves retrieving all keys from the backing store. See the method documentation for more details. Also, any method implemented in terms of keySet() is also costly.

    Neither the keySet() method nor any method implemented in terms of it is thread safe.

    The following methods are implemented in terms of keySet():

    • entrySet()
    • containsValue(Object)

    Method remove() always returns null.

    Any unchecked exceptions thrown as a result of accessing the backing store are rethrown as CollectionException.

    Author:
    Jairam Gottapu

    • Method Detail

      • entrySet

        public Set<Map.Entry<K,V>> entrySet()
        This method first gets the keys by calling the keySet() method. It then fetches each value from the underlying store using the keys by iterating over the keys. Each iteration will result in an Map.Entry object being created.

        Also the size of the entrySet depends upon the underlying store. So, if you think the underlying store is huge, avoid calling this method as this will result in large amount of memory allocation as well a considerable performance hit.

        It will be better if you could use this processor with out having to call this method.

        Throws a UnsupportedOperationException if either add or remove methods are called on the Set returned by this method.

        Throws a UnsupportedOperationException if remove is called on the iterator of the Set returned by this method.

        Specified by:
        entrySet in interface Map<K,V>
        Returns:
        The set of Map.Entry<K, V>

      • containsValue

        public boolean containsValue(Object value)
        Causes a huge performance hit. Refrain from using it. It gets the entry set from the underlying store. Then iterating over the entry set, get each value from the store and store the pair as a Map.Entry in an another java.util.Set. After this it iterates over the Map.Entry objects to find the match for the given argument.
        Specified by:
        containsValue in interface Map<K,V>
        Parameters:

        Returns:
        whether the underlying store contains the specified value.
